Yes — you can update the sales point screen with NL translations and custom title fonts. The clean way is to handle these separately:

1. **Translations** through `messages.properties` / `messages_nl.properties`
2. **Fonts** through static assets + CSS `@font-face`
3. **Screen text** through Thymeleaf `#{...}` message keys

## 1. Add NL translations

If you already have English/French messages, add Dutch in:

```text
src/main/resources/messages_nl.properties
```

Example:

```properties
salespoint.title=Selecteer uw verkooppunt
salespoint.subtitle=Kies het verkooppunt waarmee u wilt doorgaan
salespoint.continue=Doorgaan
salespoint.noSalesPoints=Er zijn geen verkooppunten beschikbaar voor uw gebruiker.
salespoint.error.title=Er is iets misgegaan
salespoint.error.message=We konden uw verkooppunten niet ophalen. Probeer het later opnieuw.
```

Then in your Thymeleaf page:

```html
<h1 th:text="#{salespoint.title}">Select your sales point</h1>

<p th:text="#{salespoint.subtitle}">
  Choose the sales point you want to continue with
</p>

<button type="submit" th:text="#{salespoint.continue}">
  Continue
</button>
```

Spring will pick `messages_nl.properties` automatically when the user locale is `nl`.

## 2. Where to put the fonts

Put the provided font files here:

```text
src/main/resources/static/fonts/
```

Example:

```text
src/main/resources/static/fonts/MyTitleFont.woff2
src/main/resources/static/fonts/MyTitleFont.woff
```

Prefer `.woff2` if available. You can keep `.woff` as fallback.

## 3. Register the font in CSS

In your CSS file, for example:

```text
src/main/resources/static/css/sales-point.css
```

Add:

```css
@font-face {
  font-family: 'SalesPointTitleFont';
  src: url('/fonts/MyTitleFont.woff2') format('woff2'),
       url('/fonts/MyTitleFont.woff') format('woff');
  font-weight: 400;
  font-style: normal;
  font-display: swap;
}
```

Then use it only for the title:

```css
.sales-point-title {
  font-family: 'SalesPointTitleFont', Arial, sans-serif;
  font-size: 32px;
  font-weight: 400;
  line-height: 1.2;
}
```

And in HTML:

```html
<h1 class="sales-point-title" th:text="#{salespoint.title}">
  Select your sales point
</h1>
```

## 4. Include the CSS in the Thymeleaf page

In your sales point page:

```html
<link rel="stylesheet" th:href="@{/css/sales-point.css}">
```

## 5. Locale switching / NL detection

If your app already uses Spring locale resolution, then Dutch should work when the request has:

```http
Accept-Language: nl
```

or if you pass a language parameter like:

```text
?salesPointLang=nl
```

depending on your current setup.

For Spring Boot, a simple config usually looks like:

```java
@Bean
public LocaleResolver localeResolver() {
    SessionLocaleResolver resolver = new SessionLocaleResolver();
    resolver.setDefaultLocale(Locale.ENGLISH);
    return resolver;
}

@Bean
public LocaleChangeInterceptor localeChangeInterceptor() {
    LocaleChangeInterceptor interceptor = new LocaleChangeInterceptor();
    interceptor.setParamName("lang");
    return interceptor;
}
```

Then URLs like this work:

```text
/sales-points?lang=nl
```

## 6. Important note about fonts

Do not hardcode fonts from your local machine like this:

```css
font-family: "Some Installed Font";
```

That only works if the user also has that font installed. Since the font files were shared with you, include them as static assets and load them using `@font-face`.

## Recommended structure

```text
src/main/resources/
├── messages.properties
├── messages_fr.properties
├── messages_nl.properties
└── static/
    ├── css/
    │   └── sales-point.css
    ├── fonts/
    │   ├── MyTitleFont.woff2
    │   └── MyTitleFont.woff
    └── images/
        └── continue-icon.svg
```

For your case, the next code change is likely:

```html
<h1 class="sales-point-title" th:text="#{salespoint.title}">
```

plus the `@font-face` block in CSS.
