Yes, but with one important distinction:

**For normal Spring Boot configuration**, YAML works:

```yaml
# application.yml
spring:
  messages:
    basename: messages
    encoding: UTF-8
```

But for **i18n translation message bundles**, Spring Boot expects `.properties` files by default:

```text
messages.properties
messages_fr.properties
messages_nl.properties
```

So for this sales point text, the recommended setup is still:

```text
src/main/resources/messages_fr.properties
src/main/resources/messages_nl.properties
```

Example:

```properties
pageTitle=Choix point de vente
salesPoints.heading=Connexion à<br>votre espace partenaire
salesPoints.title=Votre point de vente
salesPoints.description=Vous devez choisir le point de vente dans lequel vous vous trouvez actuellement.
salesPoints.confirm=Confirmer
```

```properties
pageTitle=Keuze verkooppunt
salesPoints.heading=Verbinding met<br>uw partneromgeving
salesPoints.title=Uw verkooppunt
salesPoints.description=U moet het verkooppunt kiezen waar u zich momenteel bevindt.
salesPoints.confirm=Bevestigen
```

You **can** use YAML for translations, but not out of the box cleanly. You would need a custom `MessageSource` / YAML message bundle loader. I would avoid that unless your project already has one.

Best approach:

```text
application.yml          ✅ app config
messages_fr.properties   ✅ translations
messages_nl.properties   ✅ translations
```

So yes for app properties/config, but for `#{salesPoints.title}` translations, use `.properties`.
